      "createdAt": "2026-04-18T21:06:43.479382+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "James, thank you for telling me this. Seriously — that took courage, and it matters.\n\nPlease don't apologize. You were dealing with something difficult, and you found a way to share it when it counted. That's what matters right now.\n\nI do need to be straightforward with you about one thing: diagnosing what's happening with your foot and recommending treatment is genuinely outside my lane as a coach. Even if I wanted to help you there, getting it wrong could mean real harm — and you deserve better than a guess. What you're describing — pain that's been worsening and stopping your runs — needs a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor to assess properly, and soon. They're the ones who can tell you what's actually going on and what your foot needs to heal.\n\nWhat I *can* tell you is this: pausing your runs right now isn't a setback. It's the most important training decision you can make. Protecting the tissue now is what keeps the longer road open.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I'd suggest as a clear next step: **contact your physio or GP this week** — ideally in the next day or two given what you've described. When you do, mention that the pain has been worsening progressively and that you were running through it. That history will help them assess accurately.\n\nOnce you have their guidance, come back and we'll rebuild together. I'll work within whatever they give us — whether that's full rest, walking only, cross-training, or a very gradual return. There's always a path forward from here.\n\nOne thing I want to ask, and take your time with it: **how are you doing with all of this, beyond just the foot?** Injury layoffs can be a lot to sit with."
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01A2tcH7Y9vwNfbgty8AeWY9"
    }
  ],
